\begin{frame}\frametitle{Describing Categorical Data}
\framesubtitle{Pie Charts}
\begin{definition}
A \alert{pie chart} shows the amount of data that belong to each category as a proportional slice of the circle.
\begin{itemize}
\item useful when only one variable is of interest

\item larger slices indicate larger relative frequencies
\item \textbf{Total percentage of all displayed categories equals 100}, i.e. a pie chart is deceiving of the real relative frequencies unless we display all categories
\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

Note:
The area of a plot that shows data should be proportional to the amount of data.
\end{frame}

