\begin{frame}
\frametitle{Describing Categorical Data}
\framesubtitle{Examples of bad graphical displays.}
\begin{columns}[T]
\begin{column}{0.4\textwidth}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.10]{3d_pie_chart.png}
\end{center}
\end{column}
\begin{column}{0.6\textwidth}
\footnotesize{(1) The area principle is severely violated in this pie chart. Without the 3-dimensional effect the pie chart suggests that all slices are of equal size (equal frequencies) and equally important. \\
Raising the slices to different heights (adding the 3rd dimension) and doing so in an order causes the 3-dimensional slices to be of different volumes. Different volumes, by the area principle, imply that the categories with a higher volume have higher frequencies. It is not clear, however, which of the two effects the graph is going for.   
(2) 3-dimensional pie-charts are more difficult to interpret because the third dimension typically creates a distorted effect of perspective and makes the comparison among the slices much more difficult.} 
\end{column}
\end{columns} 

